text: Poured and orangey/amber color with a decent head that faded to lacing. A slightly sweet aroma with hints of fruity hops and strong malt. Taste is very malty with a bready flavor and mild hop finish. Palate was good. Overall, one of the stronger marzens I have tasted.
user_location: Town of Maple Creek, Wisconsin, USA

text:
This is my favorite American Oktoberfest beer. It has a rich caramel flavor and is very affordable. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Tap at Capital, Middleton, WI. Clear amber pour with weak foam. Nose is 
celery, butterscotch, amaretto. Oily body, rich for style, mild diacetyl, small celery, a couple of faults.

From the bottle of the pour is slightly cloudy with a burnt orange color, the head is thick and cream colored, the aroma is yeasty and hops towards the back of the nose, the taste is caramel, lightly a marzen beer with a crisp ale note almost reminiscent of a granny smith apple, the finish is caramel and malts.

Bottle, thanks George999! Bready malt aroma with caramel and toffee notes. Pours amber colored with a thin white head with OK retention and lacing. Starts with bready malt flavors with caramel and toffee sweetness in the background. Finishes smooth with the caramel and toffee coming to the front with an almost sticky sweetness. Nice Oktoberfest.

12 oz. bottle, shared with multiple others at brew club. Pouts a medium off white head, with slight lacing, over a clear amber (SRM 9) body.....nose is moderate toasted malts with light crust, mild hops.....taste is very slightly sweet with toasted malts, slight light hops......mouth feel, light body, no alcohol, moderate carbonation. This is a clean malty lager with minimal hop bitterness. As such it falls into the style. Perhaps a bit more Munich or Vienna malt would add more character BJCP 8/3/14/4/7

12oz bottle, poured into a wide tulip. The aroma is earthy with malty notes of molasses, maple, and caramel, as well as a bit of bread dough. This turns toward apple pie / apple juice by the middle of the drink. It pours a brilliant dark honey / light caramel hue with a light effervescence and topped by a white, sudsy and foamy head that has moderate retention and a light runny lace. The taste is a medium, malty sweet with a medium light bitter spice. Its smooth and oily with a soft foamy carbonation and a medium light body that hits the palate with flavors of caramel, molasses, some spice, honey, and a bit of a vegetal / earthy hint. The finish is smooth with caramel, apple juice, and a bitter clove spice. The aftertaste is somewhat cloying with a syrupy character and a woody spice as well as apples.
One of the better octoberfests I have had. Not overly malty and somewhat like a red ale. Slightly sweet finish. Pours reddish brown. Had at Geneva national golf course

12oz bottle pours a orange/copper with a medium creamy khaki head. Aroma reminds me of a chocolate tootsie pop, caramel and toffee malt, fruity hops, mild cocoa. Taste similar to aroma, clean with a mild bitterness on the finish. Decent well balanced Marzen.

Pours a clear pale orange/amber with a robust off white head. Toasted bread aroma. Taste is sweet caramel malt all the way, along with buttered biscuits, bread dough, and spicy very mild hops. Decent and traditional.
Ok orange color, really good mix of malts, but for me the hops at the end are just slightly over balanced.
High carbonation for style. Light sweetness, caramel maltiness and a sort of honeybread flavor. Modest bitterness for the style. Good and very drinkable.

Not much here that would shock anyone. An up and down easy drinking beer. Biscuity and slightly sweet, great for a cool fall day.


---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Great example of a Märzen. Poured from a can at Badgerville in Madison, WI. Bready, with a little residual malt sweetness.
Sampled at esbls. Clear amber gold. Just a little fall flavor which is right. Grin and soft fruoty hops. Nicely done.

Nice solid Oktoberfest. Would try it again. Doesn't have an overly strong taste but just enough to have a few without being overpowering

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

This is quite an authentic rendition, with a dark, rich body of caramel malt that sports a dark orange hue, offering bread dough and understated hops beneath, sessionable, thinning out a bit on the finish.
12 oz bottle pours amber with a off white head. Aroma of malts, grain and spice. Taste is malts.

Sample at Great Taste of the Midwest on 08/09/2014: Clear bright orange color with a medium thin off-white head that recedes quickly to an outer ring. Short strings of lacing. Aroma of malt, caramel and slight hops. Light-bodied with a strong malty character and notes of hops and fruit in the background. The finish is sweet with a roasted malt aftertaste. Decent overall.
My favorite marzen by far. Great toasted sweet malt and a slight bitterness to balance. Clear, clean, crisp appearance and a refreshing clean palate. Cant ask for much more for the style.
Very nice traditional style Oktoberfest bier. Very rich and malty, good amount of bready caramel on the palate.
Very nice, with the hint of the brewery and very nice smooth features there too to find.

Draft at The bar in Appleton, WI The beer poured a clear amber with no head. The aroma and taste was of toasted malts and caramel. This was a nice Octoberfest while watching NCAA football. The medium body beer had average carbonation. Smooth finish with a hint of hops.
Bottle--high quality Oktoberfest. Solid amber color with a tiny head. Aroma of malts and taste of sweet caramel and a malt base. Toss in some toasty notes and were talking quality. Total wine.
Nice appearance. Golden brown and orange. Decent amount of flavor for an Octoberfest. Im not a big fan of Octoberfests, but this one is decent.

Tried this on tap. The aroma was caramel, bread, and a little roasty. The color was a fiery orange, clear and the head was a creamy white. The taste was a sweet medium with bitter at the end of the palette. A very drinkable beer. Palate had a medium body texture was sticky but clean during the beginning with a bitter finish.

Pours a nice looking fiery amber. Fair creamy white head, lasting. Aroma is sweet, malty, toasty, caramel. Light body but full flavored. Sweet and toasty. Enough earthy hops and bitterness to balance. Dry finish.

Smells fresh, malty, caramel, a little toasty. 
Strong malt, some caramel, toastiness. light but strong flavor. Nicely balanced, very Smooth.

Nice malty brew. Sweet and caramel malts abound. Aroma of malt and musky hops. Sort of a caramel and candied flavor. Not a bad Oktoberfest. Medium bodied and slightly sticky.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Casting central marzen aroma - lightly candied, cereal, a little dark syrup, some grassiness.  Intense, clear, bronze color.  Standard US twist-off longneck.  Good cap, OK label. Lightly sweet, a little woody, lightly bittered, a little tannic, good malting.   Medium, slick body.  Sweetish, toasted malt, graham aftertaste.  Ive not had a bad beer yet from this brewer, and they make some great lagers. Picked up a sixer of this from Market Square Liquors on a fire sale ($3.99/6, slightly after Oktober) - this was a bargain.  I use marzens a lot in my cooking, so if these dont all get swilled, they have great utility.

Tallahassee, Fl - New Leaf Market - 12 oz bottle. Pours a nice sparkling medium copper with a very slight white head. Aroma is pleasant but not very apparent with hints of caramel and ripening vegetables. Nice clean flavor with a brief hint of unsweetened chocolate, a touch of molasses and some back end ripening vegetables. Mouthfeel is thick enough. Decent.
3 ounce sampler at the Grovetoberfest Miami beer festival 10/13/12. Very good!
Too sweet, almost sugary and artificial. Thankfully its not offensive, and the taste doesnt insist on sticking around.
On tap at CBF. Poured red with a moderate head and good lacing, with an aroma, with a faint sourness. It had a sweet toasty malt flavor all the way through and was very smooth and fresh tasting.

bottle. Pours bright orange with a quick little white head that settles to a ring. Aroma has nice malt and marmalade scent. Taste has a nice subtle bitterness and sweet malt marmalade mixed throughout. Palate is slick with a fizzy carbonation and a drying finish. Pretty nice.

Outstanding! 
Great grain aroma with a bit of cookie or cake like breadieness?  Great roasted malt flavor that just pores through the whole time. Even finished with that sweet malt flavor lingering. Just a little bit of tart at the end, simple, like a period at the end of sentence.  
I liked the shit out of it!

Pours a clear amber orange. Not much aroma. Taste is malty & biscuity with little hop finish. Moderate carbonation. Overall a nice Octoberfest. 

More beer please...

12oz bottle from Binnys Lakeview. Pours a crystal clear, copper, somewhat gold tinted body with a finger-width, frothy, off-white head that dissipates slowly and leaves a nice lacing. Aroma is rich and bready malts with a medium sweetness, a light caramel, a touch of toast, and a floral fruitiness with some peaches and a light apple note. Flavor is similar. Rich and bready malts with some toast and a light caramel sweetness. A slight graininess and a light earthy hopping with a bit of a peachy fruitiness before this finishes smooth with a balanced, light-medium bitterness before leaving a medium length aftertaste. Medium body with a moderate carbonation. Overall, not a bad Oktoberfest. Some bready sweet malts with a light caramel and graininess balanced with a clean, earthy hopping and light toast note. Enjoyable enough.
Ok beer.  Kinda sweet.  Not really appealing.  I look for a much bolder flavor from an octoberfest.  Good color, no real aroma.

Wheat aroma. Pale brown color. Thick head. Malty flavor with some sweet notes. Abrupt finish. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Aroma is absent but not bad, a little sweet. Color is brown and a little cloudy, with a small white head. Taste is sweet and malty, and nice and frothy on the palate.

Thirsty Troll Brew Fest. Pour is orange gold with a white head. Aroma shows a grainy biscuit/toffee malt profile with light spice and grassy hops. Flavor shows the same with additional dried stonefruit and maybe a hint of banana. Overall body is moderate and finishes with light bitterness.
pours a copper color. carmel and malt on the nose. tastes like it smells. decent oktoberfest..

Nice looking yellowish orange copper, very clear pour with some head disapating quickly to a ring ,spotty layer of foam with some lacing.Fairly typical mineral aroma but with some nut light fruit,distict grain, light carmel and an unusually pleasant yeastbready grain aroma. In taste you pick up alot of the distinct malt with a fruit-like berry,this is pretty smooth and medium to light full bodied taste finishing crisp dry and toasty  with some citrus bitterness.Pretty decent.Nice aroma and flavor,no metallicyness.Good malt character and a nice mild bitterness balanced well with the sweet  almost nutty carmelness.

Amber with white head.  Spicy malt aroma.  Taste is spicy caramel malt.  Cinnamon, nutmeg, caramel bread dough and toasty malt.  Medium body, rather dry profile, ample carbonation.  A solid Oktoberfest.
UPDATED: DEC 29, 2013 Tap. Clear lighter amber pour. Nose is caramel. Not very carbonated. Taste is caramel, malt, and kind of flat. Okay at best.

Date: October 7, 2011 Mode: Draft Source: 508 
Good for an Oktoberfest, but not very complex or interesting.

1. Look - A deep gold color Oktoberfest with a small head and a lot of bubbles.
2. Sniff  There is a soft malty aroma and a slight metallic nose as well.
3. Sip  This is a tasty light bodied Oktoberfest it has a very smooth taste and a excellent finish.  
4. Another Look  The beer is average as far as appearance the head has dissipated and there is not lacing.
5. Evaluate  Overall, this is a well balanced easy drinking Oktoberfest.  It has a very unique smooth finish.  I would recommend Capital Brewerys take on the Oktoberfest style to all of my friends and family.
Dough/yeast and bread in the aroma.  The flavor is bready and malty.  A very solid Oktoberfest and very easy to drink.

This amber hued brew pours with a small light tan head and has a caramel and malt aroma. Fairly creamy on the palate, the taste is mostly malt with a hint of caramel and a muted hop note on the finish. This autumn brew pairs well with brats off the grill.

Serving glass: Poured from bottle into pint glass.

Appearance: Clear amber-orange with some frothy head at first but falls back too quickly.

Aroma: Toast, caramel, cherry and metallic hops.

Taste: Nice complex malts with biscuit, caramel and cherry interwoven together. Has a nice spicy hoppiness as counterbalance, which continues long after each sip.

Palate: Moderately high carbonation, medium body, crisp and dry finish. Great feel for a Marzen.

Overall: One of the better Marzens out there, although style wise it leans a little closer to a bitter Vienna. More than solid Autumn brew.

12 ounce bottle from Steves Mineral Point in Madison. Pours a clear amber with a med white head. Decent head retention and lacing. Aroma of caramel, toasted malts and a bit of a buttery note. The taste is toasted malts, berries and caramel. Faint hops. Medium bodied.
This beer is really pretty decent, but still nothing much to it.  I like some more complexity.

Thanks to BeerFMAndy for this brew. Poured into a pilsner glass.

Color is bright peach with a slight bit of copper. Not entirely transparent, though no visible haze particles. Initial head is a single finger and dies down pretty quickly into a bit of foam on top. Very mild lacing around the sides. Nose is some light, toasted malt that reminds me of a light amber ale. Some biscuit malt as well as some very mild earthy hops.

Taste is some light biscuit malt and a very mild amount of caramel and toffee. Pretty plain. There are some light earthy and floral characteristics in the background. Light creamy character. The feel is a bit light with moderate carbonation. This is a nice and simple beer without any flaws, though I wouldnt go out of my way to try it again.

Serving type: bottle

Reviewed on: 11-17-2010

The final Oktoberfest I will down this season.

Pours the classic amber color.

Smell is a bit sweeter than most but hops are also present.

Taste has a nice hoppiness to it, along with nutty, sweet malts.

Overall it is another solid Oktoberfest Beer, somewhere in the middle of the pack.

Serving type: bottle

Reviewed on: 10-10-2009 15:33:08

Pint at the Capital Tap Haus.  This is what I look for in an oktoberfest... golden hue nice dense head, light caramel cereal grain nose.  Slightly sticky palate. Caramely, bready front with a bit of dryness on the finish.  Easy to drink a few of these at one meal!
On tap at brewery, pours a clear amber with a thin whtie head, the aroma is of sweet malt and the taste is much of the same, the flavor is very smooth and enjoyable, not bad.
Not the best, but I was impressed. Great aftertaste, with a sort of sweetness to it.

12oz bottle, courtesy of MrPickles. Thanks, Andy! Pours a bright, highly effervescent orange-amber color (perfect color on this, but not surprised from Capital); creamy, fine-bubbled light-tan head with great retention and lacing; really promising pour. Softly toasty maltiness in the nose, very clean, crisp, and focused on that perfectly restrained malt character; dead-on for the style, with maybe just the slightest touch of ethanol. Medium body; lively carbonation; crisp, snappy profile; generally smooth; you really cant ask for a better mouthfeel, with a nicely interjected acidity; lightly creamy, toasty maltiness is again the core of things here; seems like a fair amount of Vienna malt, but Im just guessing here; nicely toasty, well-attenuated, with an appropriate level of mineral hop bitterness there as well; hugely rich in the maltiness for how easy-drinking this is. Great rendition. Thanks again, Andy! Medium finish of smooth maltiness, a light mineral character; nicely balanced ending. Awesome Oktoberfest.

Bottle: Pours a "fiery golden", makes me yearn for autumn. Aroma is scrumptious malt, taste is smooth. malt. deliciousness. Caramel malt on the finish with very mild hops. Simple, delicious. Wheres my mas.

12 oz bottle.  Pours a clear dark copper body with a small fizzy off-white head that fell to a wispy film.  The nose is slightly sweet toasted malt with just a minimal amount of hops, smells pretty clean.  The flavor is much the same, clean, malt driven with just a slight bit of hops on the finish to liven things up.  Lingering toasted malt.  Medium bodied with moderate soft carbonation that cuts the sweet body well.  Not bad, these guys do good things with Lagers.

12 oz bottle purchased at Blue Max in Burnsville, Minnesota. Pour is copper golden ruby, clear bodied, with a two inch white head that falls pretty quick. Aroma of malty mildly sweet straw with some leafy earth spice in the back. Taste is the grainy malt, big earthy straw, some clove spice in the back. Sweetness is a bit sharp, not too well integrated. Palate is medium to thin, normal carbonation level - easy enough to drink. Decent Oktoberfest though it got pretty cardboardy and dirty as it warmed.

12 oz bottle, pours a transparent orange/amber color with little head. Aroma is sweet and spicy with some vegetable noticed. Flavor is well balanced between sweet/spicy/bitter with a little more spicy. Palate is full and satisfying with a great aftertaste. Excellent beer, well made Marzen.

Pours a nice bright orange color with a good head and good lace. The aroma is faint but malty with some mild hops. This beer is smooth, perhaps more smooth than I would prefer but there are lots of nice things going on in the flavor, this has a wonderful bitterness both very apparently from the hops and it a very herbal sort of bitterness as well. The maltiness is bright and has some noticeable nuttiness.

slight nuttiness on the nose,,,cant pick up much else. Amber pour witha  white head that disappears almost immediately. Refreshing, notes of caramel and toasted nuts. smooth mouth feel. mediocre palate.

Bottle - Pours clear amber with a cream-colored frothy head. Nose is malty and a bit sour, but muted. Definitely not a malt bomb. Taste is a bit of malt and sweetness like syrup or honey. Theres a hint of hops on the finish, but just not a lot of flavor. Its kind of thin, and warms just a bit as it goes down the throat. Just an off-putting beer that simply doesnt taste very good.
Bottle. Pour was deep golden with aroma of caramel, toffee, toasted malt, and light fruit. Flavor is bready with a crisp hop finish with light caramel.  nicely blended.

Ach du lieber mein kinder!  Ein Octoberfest?  What a surprise (or not).  its OK.  But lets face it: when you are ready to get your goof-on, you are gonna strap on the Blatz, and get jiggy with it.  This Octoberfest is spicy and just a little bit sassy.  Thats right: sassy.  Its not complete junk, but side effects of over-indulgence may include (but is not limited to) anal trauma, liver toxicity, expanding girth, soiled Blousers (Blatz trousers for the uninitiated), marital woes, and the belief that you can dance like a star (you cant).
 Keep a couple of these on hand, for your after dinner treat on a cold fall evening, but stick with Blatz for taste, sophistication, and the ability to impress supermodels with your Erfahrenheit und schmeckt.  Dont question it, mein Fuhrer!

Clear amber with a thin white head. Aroma of caramel, toast, honey, and herbs with a hint of spice. Light medium watery body with a moderate amount of carbonation. Nice malty flavor of caramel, toast, apple, and nuts with hints of herbs and spice. Very smooth and refreshing. Another solid offering from Capital, but pretty standard. Good.
Orange, clear pour with spotty, off white head. :Leafy aroma with cracker, nutty, caramel malt. Flavor is caramel with leafy hops. Good for the style, but Oktoberfests kinda suck.

pours copper/ dark gold with thin head.
Aroma is roasted malt, some nuttiness, burnt caramel.
Flavour is pretty decent. Caramel sweetness, some toasty tones. dry lightly bitter finish.

Sampled at Famous Liquors Fall /Oktoberfest Tasting in Lombard, IL. Poured a gold/amber with a foamy, off white, fairly lasting head and lacing. Pretty good for plastic. The aroma was some toasty malt and a hint of caramel. The flavor added some subtle hop bitterness, light creaminess to the tongue, and some pleasant dryness to the finish. Standard but good Marzen.

12oz bottle.  Pours a very clear but rich glowing orange amber with a very fine dense white froth.  Super rich aroma for a marzen, rich like creamy vanilla, cleaner munich malt sweetness, nice spiciness.  Flavor follows but with some leading bitterness, medium sweetness, creamy and round, softer, doughy, just a touch vegetal, and some alcohol.  Medium bodied, smooth, heavy, fine fizzy carbonation.   Something is a little bit off with this...
Clear, copper color, medium, white head.  Hints of malt in the aroma.  Lot of malt flavor, some caramel.  Some hop bitterness at the finish, medium bodied.  Typical American Oktoberfest, drinkable.

12 oz bottle.  Pours a fiery orange color, with a slight off-white head that dissipates quickly.  Malty aroma, just a hint of malt.  Some citrus as well.  Flavor is smooth and malty.  Palate feels light.  Overall a good Oktoberfest beer.

Draft at the OF.  Hazy tan-amber color with a minimal oily head.  Big amber-caramel aroma.  Super sweet diacetyl bomb.  Lots of caramel/butterscotch straight up dominates.  Probably one of the worst Oktoberfests Ive had.  The whole batch should have been drainpoured.  Trash.
Pours copper orange with creamy off-white head.  Sweet n spicy aroma.  Good match of bitterness to maltiness.  Will always be one of my favorites.
Very solid Oktoberfest. Nice malty backbone with a good roasted bitterness and smooth taste that carries you though the fall trees.

Pours darkish orange with a 1-2 finger creamy off white head. Aroma is grain, toasted grain, caramel and some floral notes. Flavor is toasted grains, fresh baked bread, nice caramel and some floral hops. FInish is planty hops and a toasty caramel fade. Palate is thin to medium bodied with a slick feel most of the way through, drying slightly to the finish. Good stuff, not the greatest marzen ever but quite tasty.

Bottle, picked up at Johns Grocery in Iowa City, IA. Opened with Tom at the "What this town needs is an IHOP" tasting. Light orange, clean milk-white head. Fresh-sawn pine board aroma, dill, just a faint toasty note. Simple bready sweetness, tingly wet garden hops. Very fresh and bright.
Pour was a pale orange with off white head aromas malts and bread tastedof caramel and malts over all a solid marzen
Draught at GABF 2008. Clear amber - white head. Citric, light malty, sweetness, pilsner malty, knækbrød, grainy, crispy, toasted. Boring.
Average Oktoberfest at best.  Medium amber clear color.  Medium white head.   A little back end bitterness in the finish.  Pretty bland.
Bottle.  Poured a clear orange/amber with a thin off white head.  Aroma of sweet malt and toffee.  Flavor was sweet malt with caramel and bread.  Good beer, but could be better.

12 oz bottle from Steve’s in WI.  Pours a clear orange with a beige head that fades.  Sweet malts a touch of toffee and marzen in the nose.  Lightly sweet flavors some charred malt, toffee, marzen, bread, touch of bitterness.  Drinkable and decent but it could use more of a hop presence.

Bottled sample. Pale amber in colour with very strong carbonation. Aromas of heavy malts, caramel, and a bit of bread dough. Fairly sweet in the mouth with more caramel and mild bread notes. There’s a faint suggestion of leafy hops somewhere in there too. A little light in the body and in toasted malt notes for the style. Drinkable enough, but a little bland overall.

More golden than amber, fairly high on clarity scale. Big white head that recedes in center, leaving foam on interior of glass rim. Smells a tad skunky upon first whiff. I’m smelling toffee pretzels...really a tasty aroma. Flavor is where this Oktoberfest beer really shines...sweet and malty and caramelly. Really nice. On a pure drinkability scale, I have to give this one the edge over Sam Adams’ Octoberfest, which is another leader in the category. I could see myself in a tent in Bavaria quaffing liters of this elixir.

UPDATED: OCT 4, 2008 Golden/copper color with a thin but persistent off white head. Aroma of floral hops with a hint of citrus. Roasted caramel malt taste with a creamy mouth feel. A little  malty but a nice brew and a great Octoberfest.
I suppose one of the better Oktoberfests I’ve tried-- although not one of my fav styles.  Still think Ayinger is better, although Capital does a decent job with lagers.

UPDATED: SEP 29, 2008 12oz bottle. pours clear copper with small white head. nice floral hop aroma with some toasted malt. flavors are crisp, grainy, toasted, caramelly finish. one of the better american bottled versions.

UPDATED: SEP 30, 2008 Small yellowish head over clear pale-amber beer. Extremely fruity nose, rosehipsjam, caramelmalts in force. Bready, but with a leafy, near-bitterish tang, that is very welcome, relieving the more classical sweet, malty, caramel-fruity notes. Retronasal again rosehipsjam. Bit spritzy MF, slick, but not much body. Not bad, even when, considering this an Oktoberfestbeer, Id hate to have to drink liters of this.  Thanks, DA!
Oktoberfest tasting Three Cellars Milwaukee.  One of the better US Oktoberfest brews I have had.  Brown sugar and almond and some light malts.
Clear amber with a tin off-white head.  Aroma of sweet malt, spice, yeast and earthy hops.  Taste of  sweet malt, yeast, spice and apple.  Malted as expected but decently balanced.  Semi dry finish.
malty, caramel on nose. flavor very clean, with nice clean finish, nicely balanced. one of the top domestic oktoberfest beers.

Malty, malty, malty with some malt in the background.  Some hop presence doesn’t quite balance it, but makes it so it’s not overly-overmalted.  One of the best examples of a Oktoberfest I’ve had.  Well done, Capital.

UPDATED: MAR 9, 2009 Bottle, pilsner glass.  Pours a clear, dark amber-orange, with about two fingers of white head.  Head disspitates, but leaves a nice lacing, and a ring is maintained by ongoing effervescence.  Aroma is deliciously yeasty, like rising dough, some fruity notes in the background.  Full-bodied malt flavors, some peachy notes around the edges.  Has the mellow body of an apple cider, but not the up-front crispness.  Finish is bready, like hardtack, with just a little hoppy bitterness finally showing through.

Bottle / 18 Aug 08
Intense, Munich malt aroma, little hop aromas
Dark orange, clear, off white head, low retention
Munich Malt flavor dominates, very little hop bitterness, not much hop flavor
Med Body, Lt Carb
Decent Oktoberfest.  A malt bomb that probably won’t disappoint.

A pretty decent marzen in my opinion. Pours a dark amber colour, with a medium sized head with great retention. sweet malty aromas with soft caramel, toffee and grain in the taste. Finishes very smooth.

Bottle into Lager glass.  Pours a pleasant copper-orange with a full, thick white head that left behind complex lacing.  Aroma is lightly roasty malts and oven-fresh breads, just like a good Marzen should smell.  Flavor was rich: sweet maltiness, some nice toasty biscuit and sweet hops underneath.  Felt loose and fresh in the mouth with nice lingering flavor, which seemed to even into a tree nut sort of vibe as time passed.  Not my favorite Oktoberfest, but one of the better ones Ive had recently.  Seems much closer to the intended full flavor of the breed that many versions seem to lack.

12oz bottle.  Pours a cloudy copper/amber color with a wispy lacing on top and excellent effervescence.  Aroma is sweet and full, with a largely malty scent complemented by caramel, floral hops, and yeast.  Taste is medium-bodied and very fruity, with notes of banana and peach alongside caramel, syrupy hops, and a bit of spices and roasted malt.  Rather light and fruity for an Oktoberfest beer, but it works.

A nice, cloudy orange with strong hints of brown sugar and almond. Perhaps a bit light on the aroma, its flavor blossoms to a slightly nutty, even earthy tone and a warm and even finish that bears notes of yeast, malt, wheat, and tangerine. Pair with a smokey cheese and slices of Anjou pear.

(Bottle) Found a bottle of this left over from 2007 at a place in Madison a couple of weeks ago. Pours an orange/light amber color with about a half inch of dense white head. Aroma of maple syrup and sweet caramel. Taste includes more in the way of nut, with hazelnut standing out in my mind. Sweet malts also introduce a doughy feel towards the finish. Very good palate and average carbonation. A tasty beer!
NIce roasted aroma.  Nice med. bodied beer with almost a nutty malt flavor.  This is not only my favorite fest but one of my best to drink.

May 2007 - Wow, I dont get the knocks by some of my pals on this one.  Pours dirty amber color, nice head and great lacing.  Aroma of roasted malts, toast.  Flavor was sweet toasted caramel, some peppery spices and a decent hop finish...a nice blend of sweetness and toast.  Rich and full mouthfeel.  Well done.
Bottle. A amber beer with a off-white head. The aroma is of rye bread and caramel malt, the taste is sweet caramel malt, rye bread and light hoppy. Medium body with a sweet finish.

(Bottle 35,5 cl) Courtesy of Skyview. Slightly hazy amber golden with a small, creamy, off-white head. Sweetish, malty nose. Medium body with lightly sweet malts and a somewhat biscuity touch. The finish is dry. Somewhat close to a Heller Bock. 171107

Bottled. A hazy orange-red beer with a thin beige head. The aroma is sweet with strong notes of fruit - especially peaches, as well as notes of malt and berries. the flavor is sweet with notes of dusty German hops combined with light notes of alcohol, leading to a dry and slightly bitter finish. OK, but nothing special.

via Bockeyhorsey via Fantsy Baseball

Nice amber color with a sweet aroma.  Sweet malty taste with a hint of bitterness at the end.

Dark amber in color, off white head that dissipates quickly. Aroma is caramel, some dough and roasted nut. Flavor leans more heavily to the doughy but sweet as well. Nice balance, medium body. Seems a bit "bigger"than the German offerings of the style.
nice rish malt flavor traditional one here whcih is good. very blanced and smooth with enough hops for a small bite on the palate nice beer guys thank a ton!

Another good offering from Capital that sets itself apart from the rest of the generic oktoberfests.  Grainy nose and caramel malt and the same old color.  But the floral hops in the body makes a nice addition to the the malt character.

Had this beer on 6/23/2000.  Aroma is a sweet carmely malt scent.  Color is a bright golden brown with very light carbonation and an ok head.  Taste a bitter malt flavor.  Starting with medium body it goes down with a sour funk.  Finish is a somewhat dry malt flavor with a bitter end.  Its just not a good Octoberfest.

Pours a deep copper with a thick bubbly off-white head that settles to 1/4".  Aroma is of light fruitiness, caramel, and some light grassiness.  Taste is of caramel, light fruitiness, light hop bitterness.  Mild carbonation and easy on the tongue.  A dead on example of the style.

Copper with decent, creamy white head / Clean grain nose / Light to medium body with some creaminess and light, sweet finish / Flavors of grain and honey with undertones of caramel / Well made but not special.

Tasted on tap. This marzen pours a medium brown color. Small sized white foamy head. Aroma is malty and sweet. A medium bodied marzen. The malts are caramel and sweet. The hops are earthy and floral. Nice balance. Good carbonation. Very drinkable, ya! Mouthfeel is full. Finish is clean and smooth. Aftertaste is sweet.

12oz bottle - Pours a red copper color with very lttle head that fades to nada. Smells like cranberries and fruit. Flavor is also like cranberries with a spicy feeling on tongue. Overall an OK fall beer. It would be great on Thanksgiving, you have the cranberry taste in the beer!

Pours a fiery orangish color, with very little head.  Nice grainy, roasted malt nose.  Very okfest style nose.  Flavor is fairly well balanced with a nice sweet roasted okfest sweet malt and a nice dose of floral hops on the finish.
user_location: Farewell Minny; Hello Puyallup, Washington, USA

text: This is a decent Marzen, but just not that much worse than the "real" German Marzens available for a buck or two more.  I love the orange color and lacy head, and the flavor is just-off being very good.

12 oz. bottle courtesy of Bockyhorsey - Pours a clear amber color with a medium size off white head.  Nice lacing.  Aroma is toasted malt and light herbal hops.  Flavor is toasted malt, light esters, and spice.  Medium body.  A decent beer.  Thanks Bill and Wendy.

Picked up 12-oz bottle from friends at Central Beer Dist. near Wausau, WI. Pours a clear orange amber brew with a thin off-white head that dissolves to a fine film and white ring. Aroma of caramel, dry nuts, some grass hops and a touch of pepper/spice. Taste is average carbonated, medium body, with some toffee and roasted malt flavors. Finish is a little gritty, with a little apple aftertaste.

UPDATED: SEP 20, 2007 Poured from a 12 ounce bottle, orange-brown with a thin white head. Aroma was faint with notes of malt, hops and a touch of fruit or citrus. The flavor is a balance of malt and hops. The finish adds a touch of bitterness.

Even at a year old, the best of a recent bunch of O-fests I dug out of the closet.  A big, full body without too much stickiness, a full caramelly mouthfeel and a lovely deep sweetness that avoid the thin reedy saccharine profile of many sweeter beers.  Malt has hints of toffee, biscuits, pepper, and the accompanying hops give the slightest twinge of hay and fall.

The pour was an bland amber color with small head and no lacing.  Aroma was of spices, sweet caramel and you could smell the alcohol.  Flavor was of caramel (was over done) and some grassy hops, little bit of a bitterness to it as well.

Poured an amber color with a thin head, weak retention, near nil lacing. Aroma was caramel, a little bit of alcohol, some spicing with light pepper notes. The flavor was caramel (too much, loses any toasty notes until it warmed, which wasnt expected as things like that often get worse with temp), slight alcohol, a little bit of grass in the spicey hop finish. Mouthfeel was zingy and sticky at the same time. This was like a little bit of a stronger version of the Winter Skal I had, but not in an improved sense, flavor was too caramelly and it wasnt nearly as crisp. An ok beer, but not excellent.

pours an off brownish red color w/ a light soapy off white head and some ok lacing.  Aroma is fairly typical for an okt.  some sweet roasted grains light carmels hints of plum i think.  Avg palate.  Flavor is pretty avg.  Just a decent Okt

Pours a clear copper topped by a good inch of sudsy tan foam. The head recedes to a film and a thick ring, providing moderate lacing. The aroma is fruity with caramel maltiness. The beer has a nice dry toasted malt profile, lightly fruity, with caramel well in the background. The dryness and some hop bitterness really become pronounced in the finish – delicious! Medium bodied and lightly carbonated.

Mother in Law sent me a 12 oz bottle for christmas. Mild sweet spicy malt aroma. Orange body with decent head. Mild spice in the flavor which was good for me anyway. Mild sweet malt with a mild orange citrus bitterness present. Smooth on tthe palate not malty heavy that it is like spice malt sludge for some of this style. Decent brew.

Bottle.  Pours a very effervescent copper with a quickly dissipating off-white head with, little lacing.  A dry nutty malt aroma that bites the nostrils.  Dry taste, fairly mild, a faint hint of sweet malt.  Super crisp and clean with a medium body.  Unexciting, but a good example.

From a twist off 12 oz. bottle with no freshness date, but this is the fall 06 release, served in a Capital pilsener glass.

Poured a clear bright amber with a foamy, fluffy head that settled into a thin, foamy lacing, minimal amount of sticking.

Aromas of toasted grains, sweet caramel, floral and apple fruity, a little earthy spiciness in the background.

Good, steady carbonation and a crisp, smooth medium-light bodied mouthfeel.

Pleasant Oktoberfest taste, floral, earthy, lightly spicy hops, an apple fruitiness, a soft toasty, light graininess, sweet caramel malts and an apple and sweet malty finish.

Another quaffable German style lager from Capital, a seasonal I look forward to.

Bottle (12oz).  Clear medium copper with a smallish off-white fizzy head.  Nutty caramel aroma, sweet with mild spice, a hint of grapefruit zest and maybe some very light pungent hops.  Taste - roast caramel malt, somewhat toffeeish, mild herbal hops, a bit minerally in the finish.  Average body, lively slick mouthfeel, quick, oddly boozy finish with again a minerally aftertaste - not bad, but doesnt hold a candle to their autumnal fire ... seems a bit quickly made.

H-Ps Original Oktoberfest is so much better than this in terms of taste and mouthfeel there is just no comparison. Too malty and lame spice/carmel notes. Bit watery, with acidic and mineral notes that make for particularly bad after taste.
Very nice amber/orange color with a thick off white head.  Sweet, malty aroma.  Lots more sweet malt in the flavor.  Smooth finish with a very well rounded body.

Found this one bottled in DeKalb, Illinois.  Excellent Marzen style beer.  Clear, copper pour with a tan, lacy head, pleasant nose of baked bread, cinnamon and hops, goes down clean with a bit of lemon, chocolate and apple.  Finishes clean as well.  Very nice.

UPDATED: SEP 28, 2007 Pours a clear medium amber with a small quickly fading head. Aroma of light malts and light bitter hops. Flavor is of candied malts, grains. A nice clean fresh beer with a mild dryness.

12 oz. bottle
Aroma: Smokey caramel malty odor is pleasant.
Appearance: Clear amber with a decent head that lingered fairly well during the drink.
Flavor: Malty with caramel and spices.
Palate: Medium bodied and not overly dry.
Overall: Not a bad beer.  Enjoy during the Fall season.  Gotta love Oktoberfests.

Wow! really good this year, Yummo!  This year so far one of the best. This has a bit of that dryness that I prefer in this style of beer which makes it so quaffable.  Nice rich red with amber highlights. light lingerin head with distinct lace. A solid beer. Love to eat pizza with this. Hell, anything at all.

12oz bottle.  Beautiful clear blood orange hue.  Minimal spotty white head that leaves a slight cling to the side of the glass.  Smokey and caramel nose.  Toasty and cocoa.  Medium mouthfeel with an apparent biscuit bready malt flavor.  Almost dulling, but light and sticky.  Leaves the mouth and gums tingling.  Good malt note, and as it warms, the bitter hops are starting to shine through.  Then comes the caramel notes and the slight bitter burn from the hops and alcohol.  Not my favorite Oktoberfest, but it puts up a good showing.  Not quite as rounded and smooth as I like.

(12 oz bottle: Obtained in trade with Ughsmash, thanks Jason!) Flavorful, if unspectacular and borderline bizarre Oktoberfest lager with a sweet, toasty, and overly caramely maltiness, a moderately strong bitterness, at least for the style, a strange fruitiness, and a rather unwelcome perfumy flavor as well.  Hops adds a bit of spiciness to the mix.  In the nose, I pick up sweet caramel, brown sugar, an odd earthy/woody aroma, and some kind of fruitiness that occasionally reminds me of raisins, then maybe grapes, but ultimately remains elusive to unwaivering identification.  Medium bodied and sufficiently carbonated, pretty much just feels like Im drinking a generic beer.  Amber color shows nearly perfect clarity ... and precious few carbonation bubbles rising through the beer.  Large, bubbly off-white head when poured shrinks fairly quickly down to a nearly microscopic ring.  Certainly lots of interesting flavors at play here, but this strange "Oktoberfest" concoction just doesnt work for me.

Had fresh from the taps at the Capital Brewery.  It had a great finish, although at first I was not impressed with it.  One that I would readily drink again, but if given the choice there are other Capital taps I would go for first.
Amber colored, malty aroma with hints of sweetness? A sweet and very long finish, with a little bitterness. Overall not to bad.

Clear amber body with a lovely frothy white head.  Nut butter aroma with some apple skin tang.  Nutty, toasted malt flavor with a leafy, apple juice finish.  Somewhat zippy carbonation which detracts a bit from the beer.  Again, a well-made beer from Capital that I feel that I should reall like but dont.

Clear amber-orange with fluffy dense white head. Grassy, malty, sour, & hop spice aroma. Medium hop bitter, grassy sour, & medium caramel malt flavor. Hop and sour subside a bit as the beer warms -- begins to taste more like a fest. A little on the hoppy side for a fest but within style. Medium body & palate appropriate for the style. Not Capitals best and yet still quite competent.

Bubbly.  Oh, yes bubble.  Thats what really got me about this one -- the complete lively texture.  Had this draft at Angelic brewing when they told me they no longer brewed beer.  Slightly bitter with some malt flavors.  Overall, decent.  Not great.

12 oz Bottle from Armanettis, Mundelein, IL. Clear amber having small creamy white head with excellent lacing.  Light sweet malty aroma with hint of spice, molasses, fruity esters and toffee.   Soft carbonation. Medium-to-full bodied with starts with hint of sweet malt, middles on dry side, and finishes with dry bitterness.  Some echoes of Capitols Autumnal Fest and Capitols Wisconsin Ale but milder, drier and more bitter. An excellent Oktoberfest beer.

Nice clear bodied orange color with a meium white head and some lacing.  Mostly caramel malts, but theres a really nice and unexpected pepepry flavor from the middle to the back that helps keep the finish dry.

On tap in Madison before a show a few days ago, rating from memory.  Slightly fruity aroma with a nice malty base and some spices.  Beautiful, brilliant orange color with a thin white head.  Again, much like the aroma, the flavor is a mixture of caramel with a slight fruity/spicy twist.  I liked it, but havent had many Octoberfests to compare it to.

Courtesy of Bockyhorsey.

Sweet aroma. Fruit (grape dominates) and caramel malt. Orange with little head. Malty fore followed by a grape heavy middle and finish. Fruit smoothness lingers int he aftertaste. This beer has a fantastic aftertaste. It tastes better 5 seconds after you swallow than it does in your mouth.
does have a gorgeous firey dark oragne color, but after that it is a disappointment.  I expected more spices, but this is uninteresting.  Taste like dust at the bottem of the cheerio box.
user_location: Middle of no where, Ohio, USA

text:
Nice copper-amber color, creamy off-white head. 
Dusty oats and banana wheat in aroma. 
Sweet oats with a hint of lime bitterness. Seems like another great average brew from Capital. Good balance. Sweetened grape skins that remind me of Raison DEtre.
Overall, very nice and enjoyable.
Nice fall like colors of orange-red. Wasnt served with much of a head. Enjoyable. Ever So Slight sweet at the front end witha nice end.

Orange-tan.  Nose sweet caramel, a bit bready.  Flavor is rather sweet, lots of caramel malts with just a hint of biscuity crispness, still good but not particularly what Id expect in an Oktoberfest.  Sticky and chewy.  Good stuff, even if it doesnt fit the style particularly appropriately.
Pours a deep orange color with a decent head. Aroma of malty sweet caramel. Lots of nut flavor with a soapy hop taste. Some spicey flavors come out in the aftertaste.
Had this on tap before the Badgers - Indiana game at Luckys on Regent Street.  Tastes of sweet malt, mild spice and German hops.  I found it true to style, but not quite as good as their Fest beer.

bottle-pours clear orange with a nice off-white head.  malt, carmel, somewhat spicy marzen malt aroma with a tinge of apple as well.  flavors are sweet, lightly psiced and earthy/dirty malt profile.  fair bitterness for this style with those german hops.  lite finish and medium body.  there is that characteristic capital lager yeast tone going on as well.  a little bready on the finish.  not bad!

Aroma is lightly sweet and grainy, matching the main taste of dry, subtle sweetness.  A faint, warm nuttiness presents itself quickly, but fades before the finish.  A lot of malt here, but the heaviness seems to weight it down.

(12oz bottle) Crystal clear amber with small off-white head.  Aroma is moderately sweet, evokes hefeweizen -- banana and wheat, with light spice, caramel.  Taste is medium sweet, banana, some caramel, light spice, earthy.  Light-medium body.  Not bad, but not what I would call a traditional oktoberfest beer.

UPDATED: NOV 16, 2007 Pours to a dark amber body with a huge foamy white head.   Excellent lacing.  I should take a photo... The aroma is floral hops, caramel malts, spicy hops.  The flavor seems fake.  Sweet and malty, banana, light floral hops.  Seems like malt extracts and canned esters. 6, 5, 5, 3, 11 = 3.0

Pours to a filtered glowing deep rusty orange body with a thin wispy white head.  The aroma is wet leaves, maple, light cherry juice, frosting.  The flavor is maple, sweet bready malts, hazelnuts, and fruitcake.  Didnt at all make me think Oktoberfest.  Sweet palate lingers.

Nothing about this really excited me.  Poured a clear dark amber/orange with a light off-white head.  Some floral hops, roasty caramel malt, and spices hit the nose.  Malt-dominated palate with a respectable spice factor on the finish.  Flavor picked up primarily caramel and Munich malts.  Decently-crafted, but not as rich as I had hoped.
Decent Oktoberfest.  Caramel nose similar to an ESB.  Long lasting sweet bitter finish.  Not enough malt to be a true Oktoberfest, but definitely can pass as a really good amber lager.

Pours a clear deep copper with a thin, fizzy white head.  Aroma boasts lots of thick sweet caramel malt and a touch of noble hops and German lager yeastiness.  Body starts very malty, sweet, and full with a good bittering hop balance toward a crisp, yet creamy, malty finish.  A very enjoyable Oktoberfest.
Much like the Summer Fest but not quite as robust. Found myself wanting a little more sweetness and body.

Bronze in color with a small, off-white, bubbly yet creamy head, which maintains creaminess throughout the sampling, leaving formidable lacing on the glass.  Aroma is sweet and spiced; malty, with characteristics of cedar and musk.  When the beer hits the palate, it tastes slick and stretched out.  Malts are discernable - a mild sweetness from caramel and Munich malts, but less aggressively so because of lighter pilsener malts that have been incorporated.  A mild spiciness hits the back of the tongue, coupled with a grainy tactile presence.  Malt sweetness is doubling back again as it warms, taking on a taste reminiscent of a caramel apple.  Some light tobacco esters and a small trace of alcohol comes through in the last 2 ounces of the remaining brew.  This Oktoberfest is well-balanced in taste, but is not very rich.  Malts and hops are proportional, but I like more of a malt backbone in my Oktoberfests.  Im hoping Capitals Fest can deliver in the areas where this Oktoberfest was less aggressive.

Another fine example of the Marzen style Oktoberfest beers.  Quite similar to Summits version.  Has that wonderful sweet malt flavor that you just want to leave on your tongue.  Solid all around--nothing offensive.  Very pleased to have found this one by accident.  Will look for it again next fall!
This is a pretty good beer for what it is, but for some reason there is something about all the Oktoberfests Ive had that I just dont like.
I really enjoyed this beer (as I do everything from Capital).  Its a great American Ofest.  Nice caramelly flavor, and beautiful color.  This is a satisfying example of the style.

Thanks to Indra for this one!
Hazy amber pour, quickly disapating head.
Malty, yeasty in the aroma.
Good flavor, hops in the back letting malt take the forfront.  Nicely done Oktoberfest.

Nice caramelly, malty aroma. Big carbonation, beer gushed a bit from the bottle. Nice deep amber color. Big, malty flavor. Some hop spicyness towards the end, but overall a big flavorful Octoberfest beer. A taste delight.

Clear amber with a thin white head.  Aroma of caramel, toast, honey, and herbs with a hint of spice.  Light medium watery body with a moderate amount of carbonation.  Nice malty flavor of caramel, toast, apple, and nuts with hints of herbs and spice.  Very smooth and refreshing. Another solid offering from Capital, but pretty standard. Good.

Ambery/brown with thin white head. Nose is slightly caramelly and somewhat sourly yeasty. Body is a bit thin and watery, but the maltiness is pleasant and firm.  Some alcohol peaks through and some sourness as well, decent but not as good as some of their other seasonals.

Off-white head, gone quickly. Amber/caramel color. Aroma:vegetal, herbal,spicy, earthy, pumpkins. Rich maltiness, nice sweet overtones, some tingly hops. A satisfactory Oktoberfest, very smooth and easy-drinking.
Butterscotch Coloring. Creamy Head.  Not Much Aroma...Malty, Dry Hops at the End...Little Spice.  Not Much on Flavor and a Pinch Watery.. Average Oktoberfest.

Slightly dissapointed by this one, seemed a little weak to me, but my problem may have been that I had a Autumn fire before this one, and after that almost anything would taste like water I guess.  Nice color though, but I was just expecting more,  Maybe it fell victim to too high of expectations...

Deep amber with trace white head.  Nutty banana nose with some malt undertones.  Very nice malty flavor, not as sweet as some of the other O-fests that I have tried.  Very creamy mouthfeel with just a dab of bitterness on the finish.  Very nice beer, second best O-fest I have had this season
(Bottle)  Pours a clear amber body with an average-sized white head.  Aroma of caramel, nuts, and cinnamon.  Malty flaovr with some spices.

Poured from the tap, this has a deep orange body with a thin frostly head that disappeared bfore the bartender could hand it to me.  Modest carbonation.  It has a nice malty aroma, maybe a bit nutty.  Gives a creamy mouthfeel, Tastes slightly sleep, but not too bad.  A crisp, malty finish.

Bottle pours a coppery orange, large foamy off-white head, healthy carbonation, with decent lacing. &nbsp Subtle nutty aroma, light fruit hints as well. &nbsp Malts, cereal, mildly sweet, slightly nutty on first sip. &nbsp Fairly clean and crisp, decent body with an average mouthfeel. &nbsp Fairly strong malty finish. &nbsp Good! &nbsp Thanks goes out to TChrome for the trade!

Light amber/red/bronze, with a bit of head.  Sweet, nutty, caramelly aroma.  The flavor is marked by alcohol with a bit of candy.  Palate leans to the thin side.  A sweet and very long finish, with a little bitterness.

Now heres a pleasant, if not memorable, Octoberfest.  Attractive brilliant amber body, dissipating head.  Toasty malt aroma, some spicy hops.  Slight gingerbread sweetness, lots of toasty grain flavors.  Well-balanced.

Clear dark amber in color, this brew has an off white head that moderately dissipates.  The aroma is very pleasent with significant notes of caramel and lots of aromatic evidence of this beer spending time in the lagering tank.  Flavor is also quite nice with lots of toasty bread type notes and just a bit of a dry finish.  Excellent example of the style.

12 oz Bottle- Color is a clear red, with a slight orange tint to it. Tiny white head. Aroma is a deep malt, with slightly acidic touch on the nose.  Beer is slighlty thin tasting, but distinct. Malty finish, very clean. A nice beer, little short on the flavor for my taste.

Bottled. Nice Oktoberfesty copper color. Theres a good maltiness here, but also a nice snootful of German hops that doesnt appear in most "authentic" Oktos. Well-tuned to the american craft beer drinker.

Nice copper-orange color, with little head.  Slightly darker than the Fest. Big sweet malt and nice hop aroma.  Really well crafted for massive consumption of excellent beer.  Finish of toffee and caramel.  Stronger than it seems.
Bottle:  Not bad.  Fairly typical oktoberfest style.  Refreshing.  Chewy malts, light hops.

well, i like this better than the paulaner.  tastes very fresh and sweet.  and well balanced with raisins, citrus and some breadyness.  rating from memory sucks.   but i remember that this beer was good.
Not bad, but not good. Capital Fest is a MUCH better beer. This will do once you are unable to find Fest at the shop anymore, though.

OK, color is pretty nice, a little lighter than most american versions, head is OK, but not lasting. aroma is fairly standard, lightly roasted malts. fairly sweet and very lightly roasted flavor. pretty tasty stuff
UPDATED: APR 14, 2004 Nice thick head. Smell of pumpkin pie?? Very smooth. A light, reddish amber color. Capital has consistent quailty. A little sweet taste.

For an Oktoberfest beer, this looks perfect. Pumpkin orange colored with a nice frothy head. Initial malt sweetness with earthy pumpkin pie roasted fall flavors. Ends on a good note with just the right amount of spice to finish it off. Mouthfeel is a lingering draft like smoothness. One of the better Marzen styles I have had this year. Throw up the dub (W) and cheers to a good Wisconsin brewery.
Had this at the Wisconsin State Fair. Everyone thought it was special. Carmelly first taste Left a sweet taste on the tongue,nice sweet aftertaste

Another fine Wisconsin brew. This beverage hits the nail on the Oktoberfest head. Malty sweet with luscious overtones. A bit dopplebock like in raison/musky smoothness and Chewy flavor. Copper glow and wonderous. "We loves the Oktoberfest". Nice work Madison. Keep the Prairie Free. See you in '04.

UPDATED: MAY 10, 2008 12 oz bottle poured a crystal clear amber color with a real nice head and some lace.  The aroma is cookie like.  The flavor starts pretty malty, but actually is a touch sour in the finish.  The palate is good and rich and pairs well with the flavor.  Overall, this is pretty good beer.
Nice clear amber color wiht a medium semi-lasting off white head.  A strong pleasant caramel malt aroma with a surprizing west coast hop.  Smooth, sweet, full of flavor and body.  Excellent marzen.

Amber colored with a moderate head and good lacing, with an aroma that reminded me of fudge baking, with a faint sourness. It had a sweet toasty malt flavor all the way through and was very smooth and fresh tasting.
Very, very malty, sweet molasses aroma. Some off notes. Small head, off-white. Tastes like it smells. Malt fest. No bite, no hops. Plain.

A clear copper body with a thin white head that left some lace toward the top.  The aroma is very malty, grainy.  Whole grain bread, nutty, toffee/caramel in the nose.  Very earthy.  The flavor is fairly crisp and clean, refreshing and leaves almost no aftertase, good or bad.  There doesn't seem to be much hop character, but I'm not sure that's the point either.  Just a flavorful, clean beer with good biscuity, bready notes with no off flavors.

Clear bronze with plenty of red.  Generous head that, though it diminishes, remains to cover the body and catch the constant stream of redish bubbles.  Strong doughy malt aroma that also consists of sticky toffee, caramel, floral alcohol and sweet raisins.  Gentle, lightly carbonated mouthfeel - just the right amount. . . flavours are on the sweet side to start: juicy gala apples, deep red grapes, raisins. . . but take a spicy turn right at the end with some lightly peppered hops and spiced pumpkin.  Still one of my first from Capital, but one that makes me want to go out and try more of their brews.

First off, a disclaimer, this bottle is not this years batch, it was one cellared since last year, the last of a sixer. Copper hue with a good but disminishing head. Aroma hinted of apricot, floral hops, caramel, butterscotch, and spicy herbs. The taste started mildly acidic before a smooth malty sweetness appeared. Light spices and biscuit taste followed. A dry and clean finish. This medium-bodied brew has a slighty creamy and lively mouthfeel. While it was not my intention to cellar this bottle (it got lost in the back), it appears to have age gracefully without losing any characteristics I remembered from last year. I hope to get my hands on this year batch and see any difference, a happy mistake.

Here it is in August and the Oktoberfest has already hit the shelves, along with four others that were on the same shelf. Out the those, this was the only one I haven't had. A little early if ya ask me, but oh well, here wo go - Clear ambery-brownish color with a small off-white foamy head that fades, little spots of lace. Smell is a roasty sweet malt with a touch of herbal like hops and earthyness coming through. Taste is subdued roasted malts with some sweetness and slight tang coming through mostly, a touch of herbal qualities show up near the finish along with a balancing sweetness. Feel is a bit lighter then expected, even while drinking it in 85 degree heat, it is however, very smooth and easy for good drinkin'.

Light brown or i guess as the disc.says orange color,small off white head that had a little holding power.Malty aroma,mild pear and maybe a slight spiciness to it as well.Malty taste with a nice fruity presence mild hops with a slight bitterness to the taste.The after taste is kind of like a bitter orange or citrus of some kind.Pretty decent brew,and it would be a good brew to have around more often.I hate the seasonal deal and would like to see good brew more often,but i guess that would cause it to be less of a thrill if it was available year round.

The aroma is sour and "macro"-like, but the beer is dominated by smooth, subtle malts.  Sweet and crisp.  Little to mention on the hops front.  A pleasant beer; I guess this is my "Marchfest" tonight!

Malty aroma, with some honey toasted wheat bread and caramel.   Medium amber coloration, faintly hazy with a creamy, off-white head.  Flavor is rather nicely blended.  Toffee sweetness, bready malt and light cidery fruitiness combine with some faintly spicy hop bitterness.  Finishes very clean, with a malty, lightly grainy and sweet aftertaste.  Medium bodied, mouthfeel is actually somewhat lively.  A decent enough Fest style, you could do much worse.

I have a half barrel of this in my fridge right now.  Sure there are better beers, but this is one that gets high marks for everyday drinkability.  While a mild caramel flavor is  the strongest flavor in this medium bodied brew there are nice touches of biscuity toast in the back.  Lighter bodied and less sweet than some lessen the impact of this brew but make it more friendly to drink.
Fruity esters of mostly apple with some pear shades. A bit of bubblegum aroma and a touch of clove. Im really glad to have something from this brewery. Many thanks to the man Max!

Maybe its just been awhile since I had a good one, but this fest soars to the top of my list.  I partook of the festive beer hall quaffing reccomended by our own krisbierjaeger and, thought he beerhall was my folks farmhouse kitchen, the liveliness of the party was well accented by the quality of this brew.  A spiciness in here reminds me of good mulled cider and is nicely accompanied by the full, round, nut toned malt.  Faint toasted flavors, too.  Just grand stuff, really.
Honey colored beer with a big creamy head.Sweet malty nose. I like the big malty beers and this is no exception. Thanks to maxpower for this one.

Had this one in a bottle.  Nose of alcohol, slight toasted malt, hints of caramel and
flowers.  Pours a medium orange.  The white frothy head is mostly diminishing with fair
lacing.  The flavor is malty and sweet with a very alcoholic middle.  The finish is sweet and
flowery.  Moderate acidity.  The medium creamy body is fizzy and feels chalky at the
finish.

better than Goose Island this year, Capital has brewed a very middle of the road Oktoberfest this season.  I little disappointing since so many of their other beers exceed mediocrity.  The color was an attractive deep orange, but the body and flavour lacked complexity.  Not somethig I woul buy again.

This poured out of the bottle a golden yellow with a thin white head and a sweet, little adjunt nose.  I found this Octoberfest to be a little thin.  This has just a sweet taste with not much complexity.  Not the best O-fest of the season.
Bottle.  A nice dark orange color.  A spicy malty flavor the way oktoberfest beers are meant to be.

Amber liquid with average sticky, frothy foam.  Subtle notes of cinnamon, alcohol, toasted malt, and apple.  Mild, yet very enticing.  Soft mouthfeel with perfect level of carbonation.  Flavors are of heavily toasted malt, pecan, and spicy hop finish.  This remains classy and subtle, which is why I love Octoberfests so much; it is very difficult to make a subtle beer with refined flavor.
user_location: Blue Ridge Mountains, North Carolina, USA

text: It has an orange/brown color and a bit of a fire to the taste.  Unlike most beers that seem to become more dull the longer you drink them, this one picked up intensity as the pint went on.

braised carrotty color, clear; white head quickly settled to a powdered sugar-like dusting. moderate woody-orange zest nose, muffin toasty malts, rumours of alcohol. sweet and then bitter in close succession. weak carbonation promotes a feeling of being slightly watery, but in fact its medium bodied, tart and tasty. not a herculean brewing achievement, but it could be i over-thought the thing. like always, i fussed over the drink, trying to coax out some nuances and interesting similies, but the style  recommends itself rather to festive beer-hall quaffing; my single 12 ounce sample bottle aint quite enough to strike up the band.
This beer very much posseses the capital house quality.  Nice slightly spicy malt flavors finished with a slight yeasty tang.  Good firm hopping in the background.  Solid.
Good malty aroma.  Nice amber color.  Good head, but disappating quickly.  Nice roasted malty flavor.  Good mellow hops.  Slightly tangy.  Good Beer overall.
Good beer. Love the smell! But it is lacking a bit in real strong taste.

Bottle: Got a good, long lasting head on the pour. Reddish-orange in color. Malt smell. Malt dominates the taste as well. As the beer warms, gets flowery and citrusy. Not bad. Had this on tap a few days ago, and it seemed richer and more complex then. Different temperature maybe?

I love the months that proceed October, because I love Octoberfest beers. This is no exception.  While I have had much better Octoberfest beers (Water Street Brewerys comes to mind), this was a decent dark beer that I could drink often.
Pours with little head; orange/copper colored with little visible carbonation.  Aroma not as good as flavor.  Malt flavor stands out.  Perhaps a tiny bit of DMS is present.

Light clear amber color. Aroma is quite malty with a faint floral and cream corn background.  Very malty in flavor and quite bitter for style (perhaps trying to offset all the malt sweetness).  A mid echelon american otoberfest.

Slight chill hazed amber. Thin off white edge head. Light carbonation. Aroma of toasted malts and toffee. Solid body, candy coated apple sweetness. Light crispness and bitter burnt caramel aftertaste. Moderately hoppy. Very light oxidized flavor. Finishes malty sweet and bitterly balanced. Nice, considering how past October it is right now.
Not bad for an American marzen. Not great either a little weak.

This conforms to the requisite style reasonably well, but cannot be really recommended; weak and thin on the tongue, sweetish and almost insipid on the nose, with no complexity and little hop presence.  A disappointment from this good brewer; try Riverwest Stein instead.
Nice traditional interpretation of the Oktoberfest style.  Similar to Capitals Autumnal Fire, but slightly lighter.
